fields.draw_shape_text:
Getting Started

Take the time to learn how to use this drawing tool before you dive in. The instructions and videos provided will quickly show you through the entire process

How It Works

The way the drawing process works is for each species group you target, you are given an imaginary bag of 100 pennies. You will draw shapes on the map representing your fishing grounds and then place some number of pennies on those shapes. The more pennies you place on a shape, the more value or importance you are placing on it. Keep doing this until you have drawn all your shapes and used all your pennies. This process may seem overly complicated but it will allow the potential impact of MPA's on each fishery and each region to be measured much more accurately.

How many shapes you draw and how specific you are is up to you. Most people draw between 3 and 8 shapes per fishery per user group.

More Help

To get this window back after closing it, click the Help button in the upper right. Additional help can be found on our frequently asked questions page. Please do not hesitate to email fish@ecotrust.org if you need more help.


    Highly Recommended
fields.assign_groups_text:
What percentage of time do you spend fishing in each of these user groups?

[Note: You won't be surveyed for groups you don't provide a value for here. Also these values must add up to 100%. For example, if someone participates in both kayak angling and dive angling, they might enter 60% for kayak angling, 40% for dive angling and nothing for private vessel angling.]
fields.group_status_text:
Please carefully read all instructions and complete the survey. You will be asked to answer questions and draw your fishing grounds. The drawing portion of the survey can be technically challenging for some and you may get discouraged at the amount of time it will take you. This is a necessary part of the survey and provides the best representation of your fishing interests so please be persistent and seek help from others if needed. The time you'll spend on this survey is probably small compared to the time you spend fishing. This is an opportunity for your voice to be heard.

If you have questions about Ecotrust's involvement in the MLPA process and what your incentive is to reveal your fishing grounds to us, please visit our MLPA page.

We are listening to your feedback. If you have technical problems please read our Frequently Asked Questions. If you are finding the online interview too difficult to complete, please email us at fish@ecotrust.org or call us using the number provided in your registration email and we will find a way to get your information included into this process.
fields.interview_complete_text:
The fishing grounds you provided will be edited if necessary, using any bounding information you provided (e.g. north, south, east, and west boundaries). Our team will then begin the analytical process where all the surveys are aggregated to create maps of important fishing grounds for different user-group/fishery combinations.

When the initial round of analysis is complete we will conduct reviews by port group. This will provide an opportunity for groups of fishermen to give feedback on the accuracy of the regional data. Again, this will be done in such a way that your individual fishing grounds will not be identifiable. Recommendations from the review meetings will be incorporated and subsequent iterations of the analysis will be completed. The maps will then be used in evaluating MPA proposals. For each proposal, stakeholders will be able to see the potential impacts that mpa would have on a given fishery and or user group. This is a valuable tool in finding the best areas for protection while trying to minimize the impact on ocean fisheries.

Thank you, again. Your willingness to participate is greatly appreciated! If you have any questions or concerns please contact us at fish@ecotrust.org

fields.answer: The number of shapes you draw is your choice.  Most people draw anywhere from 2-10 shapes per resource.
fields.question: How many shapes should I draw?

fields.answer:
The Marine Life Protection Act is law and will be implemented.  There are stakeholders involved representing your fishing interests and they need the best information they can get.  If you provide no information or false information then that can only increase the chances of your actual fishing grounds being targeted for protection because they are essentially invisible to this process.

The information you provide will be kept condidential by us at the individual level.  Any visualizations we produce (maps) will not disclose individual fishing spots as much as possible.  A review process is in place to ensure this.

Yes, other stakeholders will have access to this information as well, but having all interests represented will ensure that the information is not used improperly.  If you have any doubt you should consider becoming involved in the process as well.  Public participation is encouraged.
fields.question: Why should I show you my fishing spots?

fields.answer: We try to make the cumulative group easier for you.  By drawing your Pre-RCA And Post-RCA fishing grounds first, you can simply pick out the best grounds from those groups and put them into your cumulative group, then redistribute the pennies.  If you haven't done any drawing yet, this will make more sense once you do and the demonstration videos will show you how to do it.
fields.question: How do I draw my fishing grounds for the cumulative group?

fields.answer: The map takes the longest to load.  People without a broadband internet connection may need to wait up to a minute or two the first time they draw shapes.  If you wait and still nothing loads then try refreshing the page. If still nothing then verify you are using a supported browser (IE 6+, Firefox 1.0+, Safari 1.2+, Chrome 2+). If you have a supported browser then next verify you have 'javascript' enabled in your browser preferences (it is by default). Seek the help of friends and family if you're unsure how to do any of these steps or email us at fish@ecotrust.org.  Another option is simply to try another computer. Computers more than 5 years old are more likely to have issues.
fields.question: Why is the page not loading correctly or not loading at all when I go to draw shapes?

fields.answer: If you didn't fish rockfish before the closure areas where created then you should only select Rockfish B (Post-RCA).  If you fished rockfish before the closure areas where created then select all 3 groups.
fields.question: Which rockfish groups should I select?

fields.answer:
The precision of your shapes is important; however, we understand that accuracy will vary between users.  Please just do the best you can with the time you have and provide us with any extra information on boundaries so that our team can make your shapes more accurate.

We also understand that you might be reluctant to share your favorite little fishing hole, while at the same time you don't want to lose it.  Just make sure your fishing hole is at least captured in one of your shapes and you put a sufficient value on it.

In most cases you should not be drawing a single shape that covers hundreds of square miles.  Tuna and other migratory species are a bit of an exception.  Split these large shapes up into multiple areas if possible and weight them separately with pennies.
fields.question: How much precision should I use when drawing shapes?

fields.answer: We understand that water temperature and other factors affect migratory patterns of species like tuna.  This will make the general area you fish larger when looking at things all together like this but often there are still specific places you fish.  Maybe certain sections of water always tend to be warmer and you tend to do better there.  Maybe you don't fish tuna unless they're within 20 miles of shore or maybe you do multi-days out 60 miles.  Maybe you don't fish tuna any further north or south than a given point.  That's the information we want to capture.
fields.question: I don't fish in the same places for migratory fish like tuna.  How do I deal with that when drawing shapes?

fields.answer: Some parts of the shape drawing are done with a right click on a two-button mouse.  Many apple computers only have one button.  The way around this is to hold the Ctrl-key on the keyboard and then click the single mouse button.  That is the same thing as using the 'right' mouse button on a two-button mouse.  Anywhere you hear to use the 'right' mouse button in the videos or instructions, just replace that with a Ctrl-click on your Apple.
fields.question: How do I do the shape drawing using an Apple computer with a single click mouse?

fields.answer: Unfortunately internet explorer 6 is an aging web browser and doesn't support the necessary map features.  Upgrading to internet explorer 7 or 8 will solve your problem.  If you can't upgrade for one reason or another, try using another browser like Firefox if you can or simply use a different computer.
fields.question: When I click to start drawing shapes I get an error saying that Internet Explorer 6 isn't supported.  What do I do?

fields.answer: We apologize.  Internet explorer simply isn't displaying it properly.  Firefox or any of the other browsers don't have this problem as far as we can tell.  Please do the best you can and use the contour lines available on the nautical charts layer if possible.
fields.question: The depth contours layer doesn't look right in internet explorer.  It has dark blue contour lines and doesn't look like the video at all.

fields.answer:
Breaking rockfish out into three groups will provide better information for decision makers than surveying for a single group alone. These data will allow stakeholders and the MLPA science advisory team to better assess potential impacts to rockfish fishermen. To better explain the groups:

The Pre-RCA group will capture where you fished before RCAs were put into place.

The Post-RCA group will capture where you fished after RCAs were put into place.

The cumulative group is where you would fish if Rockfish Conservation Areas (RCAs) didn't exist anymore. Rockfish are one of the few species that are currently closed to fishing in specific areas, also known as Rockfish Conservation Areas or RCAs. These existing RCAs will not be directly included as marine protected areas in the MLPA process. In order to better assess the impact of new proposed MPAs to rockfish fishermen, it's important to know how you would fish differently if the existing RCAs were removed. The Pre-RCA and Post-RCA groups alone do not provide enough information.

Make sense? If you still don't understand this, we apologize. Please call or email us using the contact information in your registration email and we'll help you out. Your patience is appreciated.
fields.question: Why are there 3 different rockfish groups instead of just 1 and what do they mean?
